I liked these, but my carnivorous husband did not. Texture-wise, I chilled them one hour in fridge, then formed patties and chilled again, for at least 15 minutes. I used a cast-iron skillet as needed to cook inside the house and pre- heated it well. So, the patties did not fall apart and were very, very tender and moist. One tip is that I cooked the bulgur until all liquid was absorbed and it was even a bit sticky, possibly 20 minutes on slightly higher heat than called for. I only turned them one time and they held together well and browned well in the skillet with a bit of olive oil. The mayo was good, but next time, I would use Hellman's instead of Miracle Whip, which was a bit too sweet for this application, even though I increased the fresh lime juice to two tsp. I am not fond of salmonella, and did not have time to cook eggs for homemade mayo. I served open-face on squares of homemade focaccia.

