I would have given this three forks, but the egg and breadcrumbs are a must--even with them I wouldn't try it on a grill, and I dredged the patties in additional breadcrumbs to assist with holding them together. For that reason, I took a fork off. However, I will definitely use this as a base for veggie burgers in the future. They could use just a little more flavor, but the texture and grain/protein ratio were fantastic and just what I want in a veggie burger. I think a little more spice and they would be amazing. There is a black bean burger on this site that is also great, and is more flavorful, but these had a better texture.

Rating: 4
While these burgers were a bit "loose" or lacking in body, they were really one of the best versions of veggie burger I have tried. Love the spice and taste. I made them stove top but will try them on the BBQ grill next time. Perhaps more beans will make for a better consistency and a less fragile burger. Will try that next time as well.

Rating: 4
Made these exactly as written and they turned out great. Very yummy and healthy -- we would definitely make them again.

Rating: 3
These taste great! Having said that I only give them 3 stars because of a few things. I added an egg and some torn up bread (maybe 1 cup?) as a binder because from the look of them there was no way they would stay together as written. That helped, and they stayed in one piece while cooking them in a pan. However, I feel certain they would fall apart if you cooked them on the grill (with or without my added binder). For those cooking in a pan, be patient. I cooked over medium high heat for at least 6 minutes on each side. That way you only have to turn them once, and they are less likely to fall apart. Also, four servings? My mix made 5 GIANT burgers - I could have easily gotten 8 normal sized burgers from this recipe. However, great tasting veggie burger, and I certainly will make them again.

